  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition" corresp="#Ed">
    <body>
      <div type="mūlam" rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="TNV7">
      <l>murukaṉu miraviyu māyaṉum vēntaṉum</l>
<l>varuṇaṉu<anchor xml:id="varunan"/> māka vakuttaṉar koḷalē<anchor xml:id="kolale"/></l></lg>
<p xml:lang="en">Murukaṉ, Iravi, Māyan, Vēntan and Varuṇa - [let there be an] understanding that they have assigned [them as the gods].</p>
</div>
</body>
</text>
<text xml:lang="ta" type="edition" corresp="#Ed">
    <body>
      <head xml:lang="en">Commentary</head>
      <div type="commentary" rend="parallel">
      <p xml:id="TNV7comm1">e-tu. collap paṭṭa karuviṉ uḷ atiteyvam ām āṟuṇarttutaṉutaliṟṟu.</p>
       <p xml:lang="en">The quoted [<term xml:lang="ta"><hi rend="italic">cūttiram</hi></term>] intends to make known the way in which the
       presiding deities amongst the aformentioned constituent elements occur.</p></div>
       <div type="commentary" rend="parallel">
      <p xml:id="TNV7comm2">murukavēḷum<anchor xml:id="murukavel"/> pakalōṉumāyaṉum intiraṉum<anchor xml:id="intiran"/> varuṇaṉumuṟaiyāṉē ain tiṇaikkum atiteyvam ām eṉṟavāṟu. <note>(7)</note></p>
      <p xml:lang="en">Murukavēḷ, Pakalōṉ, Māyaṉ, Intiraṉ and Varuṇaṉ are the gods for the five poetic landscapes according to the [established] order.</p></div>
      </body>
      </text>
